how Japan has learned to cope with its have-not status, using flexible and inventive national policies designed to help industries acquire what they need. The United States, on the other hand, lacking an explicit and consistent national policy, is torn between protecting domestic producers of these resources and trying to develop dependable sources of supplies abroad. The result is a haphazard and unstable raw-materials policy. This unique commingling of political and economic analysis will appeal not only to scholars of international relations, domestic political behavior, and commodity markets but also to the informed layman who wishes to understand what is likely to happen as two economic superpowers range the world to satisfy their appetites for raw materials.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aApprovisionnement. 0aCompetencia internacional. 0aCompetition, International. 0aConcurrence internationale. 0aEconomische betrekkingen. 0aGrondstoffen. 0aHandel, Kommunikation, Verkehr. 0aInternational economic relations. 0aMaterias primas. 0aMatières premières. 0aProduits de base. 0aRaw materials. 0aRelations économiques. 4aCompetition, International. 4aJapan -- Foreign economic relations -- United States. 4aRaw materials. 4aUnited States -- Foreign economic relations -- Japan. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP e-dition: Complete eBook Packagez9783110353488oZDB-23-HCO08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP e-dition: Law & Political Science eBook Packagez9783110353495oZDB-23-HLP08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP eBook Package Archive 1893-1999z97831104422120 cprintz978067441872140uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/harvard.978067441873840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674418738423Coveruhttps://ww